 an explosive chemical is defined in 19 CCR 2750.2(a)(4)(A) as the distance to an overpressure of 1 pound per square inch (psi) due to a vapor cloud explosion.  
The selected ACS for the PG&E LNG Facility is a transfer hose failure due to a sudden hose uncoupling while pumping from the storage tank to the tanker truck.  LNG is released at a rate of 175 gallons per minute, which is the transfer pump rate.  A release duration of 1 minute has been assumed for the ACS.  This is a conservative assumption based on operator experience.  It encompasses time for the operator to realize what is occurring, travel to the pump control panel, and push the off button.  No passive or active mitigation measures present at the facility have been considered in the evaluation of the ACS.  This release scenario has been modeled as both as a vapor cloud fire and a pool fire to determine which type of scenario produces the most conservative results.  
Of the two types of scenarios, the pool fire scenario provides the most conservative results for the ACS radius of influence.  Therefore, the radius of influence for this scenario has been used in determining the exposed population and public and environmental receptors for the ACS. 
Prevention Program
The LNG covered process is subject to Program 3 prevention program requirements because it is subject to OSHA?s PSM standards and is not eligible for Program 1.  The PG&E Program 3 prevention program includes the following:
?    Process Safety Information;
?    Process Hazard Review;
?    Operating Procedures;
?    Training;
?    Mechanical Integrity;
?    Management of Change;
?    Pre-Startup Safety Review;
?    Compliance Audits;
?    Incident Investigations;
?    Employee Participation;
?    Hot Work Permit; and
?    Contractors.
Chemical specific prevention steps include the ESD system as described in Section 2.1.3
